{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639829"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:10:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:10:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17790"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17790"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.08,0.67,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10504"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72370"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10504"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57840"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"539"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24516"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72370"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn western communities, it is estimated that some 30% of individuals will develop gallstones over their lifetime. For most people their presence will remain unknown, but each year some 2 - 4% of these individuals will develop symptoms. Biliary colic is the most common symptom.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately describes the symptoms of biliary colic?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Crampy, lower abdominal pain associated with diarrhoea","Dull, aching pain in the epigastric region relieved by antacids","Intermittent sharp pain in the left lower quadrant","Severe, constant right upper quadrant pain","Sudden onset of severe pain in the right lower quadrant"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EContrary to what is suggested in the description, the pain associated with biliary colic is constant in nature and not colicky. \u003Cstrong\u003ESevere, constant right upper quadrant pain\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of biliary colic. This pain results from the gallbladder contracting against a stone obstructing the cystic duct. The pain is typically severe and constant, often radiating to the right shoulder or back, and is frequently triggered by fatty meals. The pain may last anything between a few minutes and several hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntermittent sharp pain in the left lower quadrant\u003C/strong\u003E is more suggestive of diverticulitis or other left-sided colonic issues, not biliary colic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDull, aching pain in the epigastric region relieved by antacids\u003C/strong\u003E is more indicative of peptic ulcer disease or gastritis, rather than biliary colic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrampy, lower abdominal pain associated with diarrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E is more typical of irritable bowel syndrome or gastroenteritis, not biliary colic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESudden onset of severe pain in the right lower quadrant\u003C/strong\u003E is more suggestive of appendicitis, not biliary colic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Biliary colic is characterised by episodic right upper quadrant or epigastric pain due to gallbladder contraction against a stone obstructing the cystic duct.","The pain of biliary colic is typically severe, constant, and may radiate to the right shoulder or back.","Biliary colic is often triggered by fatty meals and can last from 30 minutes to several hours."],"references":["Sigmon DF, Dayal N, Meseeha M. Biliary Colic. 2023 Jul 31. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613523.","Besselink MG, Venneman NG, Go PM, Broeders IA, Siersema PD, Gooszen HG, van Erpecum KJ. Is complicated gallstone disease preceded by biliary colic? J Gastrointest Surg. 2009 Feb;13(2):312-7. doi: 10.1007/s11605-008-0729-y. Epub 2008 Oct 24. PMID: 18949524; PMCID: PMC2719723.","Johnson CD. ABC of the upper gastrointestinal tract. Upper abdominal pain: Gall bladder. BMJ. 2001 Nov 17;323(7322):1170-3. doi: 10.1136/bmj.323.7322.1170. PMID: 11711412; PMCID: PMC1121646.","Beckingham IJ. ABC of diseases of liver, pancreas, and biliary system. Gallstone disease. BMJ. 2001 Jan 13;322(7278):91-94. doi: 10.1136/bmj.322.7278.91. PMID: 11154626; PMCID: PMC1119388."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57840"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17790"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57840"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T09:11:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T09:12:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10504"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72370"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"